            <p>Ezekiel &#38; Bernheim&#44;<lb/>
                Auctioneers&#44;<lb/>
                Nos. 134 Main and 31 Hammond Streets.<lb/></p>
            <p>Cincinnati&#44; June 26th 1887.<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. Dr. S. Morais.<lb/>
                Philadelphia<lb/></p>
            <p>My esteemed friend&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>I trust you will pardon my<lb/> seeming neglect in not writing to you at an earlier<lb/> date&#44; tendering my heartfelt congratulations on the<lb/> event of the honor conferred upon you by the<lb/> university of my native state.  with much pleasure<lb/> have I perused in the various Jewish Journals<lb/> the truthful encomiums passed upon your worth<lb/> <sic>entitleing</sic> you above all other men to the dis&#45;<lb/>tinction with which you have been honored.  It<lb/> affords me double pleasure when I think that the<lb/> estimate which I have uniformly placed upon you<lb/> as a teacher in Israel has been so amply re&#45;<lb/>warded.  May the almighty in His infinite mer&#45;<lb/>cy grant you <sic>lenght</sic> of days&#44; endowed with health&#44;<lb/> and rewarded by your dear children to enjoy<lb/> the crowning diadem of your ministerial career.<lb/>  With love and affection to you and dear ones&#44;<lb/> I remain as ever&#44; your true friend&#44; Jacob Ezekiel<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
